<br>
Sorry to sidetrack, but this caught my attention.<br>
<br>
See there are many forms of compensation.<br>
<br>
Commission<br>
Salary<br>
Hourly<br>
Contingent<br>
Flat Rate<br>
Tiered<br>
Tipped<br>
...many others that don't come to mind, and are often variations on those listed above.<br>
<br>
Each of these has pro's and con's.<br>
<br>
Yes, that persons 'job' is to serve you coffee.  But part of that job is to get paid and you &quot;the patron&quot; get to decide exactly what that's worth.  Whereas most other services/jobs/industries would just stiff you with the bill, where worker compensation is already figured in.<br>
<br>
For some reason tipped is the one that gets the largest amount of press, why?  Because you directly control how much the person earns?<br>
And tipped usually makes the least amount of difference in a patrons wallet?  A dollar for that cup of coffee? 15% on that  $60 dinner?  Pennies compared to the 20% commission that salesman just made when you rolled off the lot in your shiney SUV.<br>
<br>
What's the difference? Simple, you didn't see the 20% written anywhere.  Yet, you do see the dollar laying on the table being snapped up by the waitress.<br>
<br>
Ceru<br>
